Deploy a TypeScript Lambda function behind API Gateway using AWS CDK. This setup handles JSON request/response with proper typing.

```typescript
// lambda/get-user.ts
import { APIGatewayProxyEvent, APIGatewayProxyResult } from 'aws-lambda';

export const handler = async (event: APIGatewayProxyEvent): Promise<APIGatewayProxyResult> => {
  const userId = event.pathParameters?.id;

  if (!userId) {
    return {
      statusCode: 400,
      headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
      body: JSON.stringify({ error: 'Missing user ID' }),
    };
  }

  try {
    // Fetch from DynamoDB or other source
    const user = { id: userId, name: 'Alice', email: 'alice@example.com' };

    return {
      statusCode: 200,
      headers: {
        'Content-Type': 'application/json',
        'Access-Control-Allow-Origin': '*',
      },
      body: JSON.stringify(user),
    };
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error fetching user:', error);
    return {
      statusCode: 500,
      headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
      body: JSON.stringify({ error: 'Internal server error' }),
    };
  }
};
```

Install types: `npm install -D @types/aws-lambda`. The `APIGatewayProxyEvent` type provides full type safety for path parameters, query strings, headers, and body. Always return explicit `statusCode`, `headers`, and `body` — API Gateway requires this exact shape.

AWS CDK defines infrastructure as TypeScript code. This stack creates a Lambda function, DynamoDB table, and REST API.

```typescript
import * as cdk from 'aws-cdk-lib';
import * as lambda from 'aws-cdk-lib/aws-lambda';
import * as nodejs from 'aws-cdk-lib/aws-lambda-nodejs';
import * as dynamodb from 'aws-cdk-lib/aws-dynamodb';
import * as apigateway from 'aws-cdk-lib/aws-apigateway';
import { Construct } from 'constructs';

export class UserServiceStack extends cdk.Stack {
  constructor(scope: Construct, id: string, props?: cdk.StackProps) {
    super(scope, id, props);

    const table = new dynamodb.Table(this, 'UsersTable', {
      partitionKey: { name: 'pk', type: dynamodb.AttributeType.STRING },
      sortKey: { name: 'sk', type: dynamodb.AttributeType.STRING },
      billingMode: dynamodb.BillingMode.PAY_PER_REQUEST,
      removalPolicy: cdk.RemovalPolicy.RETAIN,
      pointInTimeRecovery: true,
    });

    table.addGlobalSecondaryIndex({
      indexName: 'GSI1',
      partitionKey: { name: 'GSI1PK', type: dynamodb.AttributeType.STRING },
      sortKey: { name: 'GSI1SK', type: dynamodb.AttributeType.STRING },
    });

    const fn = new nodejs.NodejsFunction(this, 'GetUserFn', {
      entry: 'lambda/get-user.ts',
      handler: 'handler',
      runtime: lambda.Runtime.NODEJS_20_X,
      architecture: lambda.Architecture.ARM_64,
      memorySize: 256,
      timeout: cdk.Duration.seconds(10),
      environment: {
        TABLE_NAME: table.tableName,
        NODE_OPTIONS: '--enable-source-maps',
      },
      bundling: { minify: true, sourceMap: true },
    });

    table.grantReadData(fn);

    const api = new apigateway.RestApi(this, 'UserApi');
    api.root.addResource('users').addResource('{id}').addMethod('GET',
      new apigateway.LambdaIntegration(fn)
    );
  }
}
```

`NodejsFunction` automatically bundles TypeScript with esbuild. `ARM_64` architecture is ~20% cheaper than x86. `grantReadData` creates the minimum IAM policy automatically.

Single-table design stores multiple entity types in one DynamoDB table using composite partition and sort keys. This enables efficient queries without joins.

```typescript
import { DynamoDBClient } from '@aws-sdk/client-dynamodb';
import { DynamoDBDocumentClient, PutCommand, QueryCommand } from '@aws-sdk/lib-dynamodb';

const client = DynamoDBDocumentClient.from(new DynamoDBClient({}));
const TABLE = process.env.TABLE_NAME!;

// Key design:
// User:      pk=USER#123        sk=PROFILE
// Order:     pk=USER#123        sk=ORDER#2024-01-15#ord_abc
// Product:   pk=PRODUCT#456     sk=DETAILS
// GSI1:      GSI1PK=ORDER#ord_abc  GSI1SK=USER#123

async function createUser(user: { id: string; name: string; email: string }) {
  await client.send(new PutCommand({
    TableName: TABLE,
    Item: {
      pk: `USER#${user.id}`,
      sk: 'PROFILE',
      GSI1PK: `EMAIL#${user.email}`,
      GSI1SK: `USER#${user.id}`,
      type: 'User',
      ...user,
    },
    ConditionExpression: 'attribute_not_exists(pk)',
  }));
}

async function getUserOrders(userId: string, limit = 20) {
  const result = await client.send(new QueryCommand({
    TableName: TABLE,
    KeyConditionExpression: 'pk = :pk AND begins_with(sk, :sk)',
    ExpressionAttributeValues: {
      ':pk': `USER#${userId}`,
      ':sk': 'ORDER#',
    },
    ScanIndexForward: false, // Newest first
    Limit: limit,
  }));
  return result.Items;
}
```

Key principles: Prefix keys with entity type (`USER#`, `ORDER#`). Use sort key for relationships and time-ordering. GSIs enable inverse lookups (find user by email, find user by order ID). `begins_with` on sort keys enables efficient range queries. This eliminates the need for multiple tables and cross-table queries.

Lambda execution roles should follow least-privilege. Here's a CDK example with specific resource ARN scoping.

```typescript
import * as iam from 'aws-cdk-lib/aws-iam';
import * as cdk from 'aws-cdk-lib';

// CDK constructs handle most permissions automatically:
table.grantReadWriteData(lambdaFn); // Scoped to this table only
bucket.grantRead(lambdaFn);          // Read-only on this bucket
queue.grantSendMessages(lambdaFn);   // Send only, not receive

// For custom policies, be specific:
lambdaFn.addToRolePolicy(new iam.PolicyStatement({
  effect: iam.Effect.ALLOW,
  actions: [
    'ses:SendEmail',
    'ses:SendRawEmail',
  ],
  resources: [
    `arn:aws:ses:${cdk.Aws.REGION}:${cdk.Aws.ACCOUNT_ID}:identity/example.com`,
  ],
  conditions: {
    StringEquals: {
      'ses:FromAddress': 'noreply@example.com',
    },
  },
}));

// WRONG: Never use wildcard resources in production
// lambdaFn.addToRolePolicy(new iam.PolicyStatement({
//   actions: ['dynamodb:*'],
//   resources: ['*'],  // BAD: Access to ALL DynamoDB tables
// }));
```

**Equivalent CloudFormation JSON policy:**
```json
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [{
    "Effect": "Allow",
    "Action": [
      "dynamodb:GetItem",
      "dynamodb:PutItem",
      "dynamodb:Query"
    ],
    "Resource": [
      "arn:aws:dynamodb:us-east-1:123456789:table/users",
      "arn:aws:dynamodb:us-east-1:123456789:table/users/index/*"
    ]
  }]
}
```

Always include index ARNs (`table/*/index/*`) if the Lambda queries GSIs. CDK's `grant*` methods handle this automatically. Use `conditions` to further restrict actions (e.g., specific SES sender addresses).

Cold starts add 100ms-5s latency to Lambda invocations. The duration depends on runtime, package size, VPC configuration, and initialization code.

**Measure cold starts:**
```typescript
// Look for 'Init Duration' in CloudWatch logs
// REPORT RequestId: xxx Duration: 15.5 ms Billed Duration: 16 ms
// Memory Size: 256 MB Max Memory Used: 89 MB Init Duration: 423.45 ms
```

**Optimization 1 — Move SDK init outside handler:**
```typescript
import { DynamoDBDocumentClient } from '@aws-sdk/lib-dynamodb';
import { DynamoDBClient } from '@aws-sdk/client-dynamodb';

// Initialize OUTSIDE handler — reused across warm invocations
const client = DynamoDBDocumentClient.from(new DynamoDBClient({
  maxAttempts: 3,
}));

export const handler = async (event: any) => {
  // Client is already initialized on warm starts
  const result = await client.send(/* ... */);
};
```

**Optimization 2 — Use ARM64 and minimize bundle:**
```typescript
// CDK configuration
const fn = new nodejs.NodejsFunction(this, 'Fn', {
  architecture: lambda.Architecture.ARM_64,  // 20% cheaper, often faster
  memorySize: 512,   // More memory = more CPU = faster init
  runtime: lambda.Runtime.NODEJS_20_X,
  bundling: {
    minify: true,
    sourceMap: true,
    externalModules: ['@aws-sdk/*'],  // Use Lambda-provided SDK
    treeshaking: true,
  },
});
```

**Optimization 3 — Provisioned concurrency:**
```typescript
const alias = fn.addAlias('live');
alias.addAutoScaling({ minCapacity: 2, maxCapacity: 10 });
```

Other tips: Avoid VPCs unless necessary (adds 1-2s cold start). Use `@aws-sdk/client-*` v3 (modular) not v2 (monolithic). Lazy-load rarely-used imports.

Presigned URLs let clients upload directly to S3 without passing files through your server. The URL expires after a set duration.

```typescript
// Lambda: Generate presigned upload URL
import { S3Client, PutObjectCommand } from '@aws-sdk/client-s3';
import { getSignedUrl } from '@aws-sdk/s3-request-presigner';

const s3 = new S3Client({});

export const handler = async (event: APIGatewayProxyEvent) => {
  const { filename, contentType } = JSON.parse(event.body || '{}');
  const key = `uploads/${Date.now()}-${filename}`;

  const command = new PutObjectCommand({
    Bucket: process.env.BUCKET_NAME,
    Key: key,
    ContentType: contentType,
    Metadata: { 'uploaded-by': event.requestContext.authorizer?.userId || 'anonymous' },
  });

  const uploadUrl = await getSignedUrl(s3, command, { expiresIn: 300 }); // 5 minutes

  return {
    statusCode: 200,
    body: JSON.stringify({ uploadUrl, key }),
  };
};
```

**Frontend — direct upload:**
```typescript
async function uploadFile(file: File) {
  // Step 1: Get presigned URL from your API
  const res = await fetch('/api/upload-url', {
    method: 'POST',
    body: JSON.stringify({ filename: file.name, contentType: file.type }),
  });
  const { uploadUrl, key } = await res.json();

  // Step 2: Upload directly to S3
  await fetch(uploadUrl, {
    method: 'PUT',
    body: file,
    headers: { 'Content-Type': file.type },
  });

  return key; // Store this in your database
}
```

S3 bucket CORS must allow PUT from your domain. Set `ContentType` in the command to match the actual upload — mismatches cause 403 errors. The 300-second expiry balances security and usability.

SQS decouples synchronous API responses from slow background processing. Lambda polls the queue automatically and processes messages in batches.

```typescript
// CDK Stack
import * as sqs from 'aws-cdk-lib/aws-sqs';
import * as lambdaEventSources from 'aws-cdk-lib/aws-lambda-event-sources';

const dlq = new sqs.Queue(this, 'DLQ', {
  retentionPeriod: cdk.Duration.days(14),
});

const queue = new sqs.Queue(this, 'OrderQueue', {
  visibilityTimeout: cdk.Duration.seconds(60),  // Must be >= Lambda timeout
  deadLetterQueue: { queue: dlq, maxReceiveCount: 3 },
});

const processor = new nodejs.NodejsFunction(this, 'ProcessOrder', {
  entry: 'lambda/process-order.ts',
  timeout: cdk.Duration.seconds(30),
});

processor.addEventSource(new lambdaEventSources.SqsEventSource(queue, {
  batchSize: 10,
  maxBatchingWindow: cdk.Duration.seconds(5),
  reportBatchItemFailures: true,  // Partial batch failure support
}));
```

```typescript
// lambda/process-order.ts
import { SQSEvent, SQSBatchResponse } from 'aws-lambda';

export const handler = async (event: SQSEvent): Promise<SQSBatchResponse> => {
  const batchItemFailures: SQSBatchResponse['batchItemFailures'] = [];

  for (const record of event.Records) {
    try {
      const order = JSON.parse(record.body);
      console.log('Processing order:', order.id);
      // Process order...
    } catch (error) {
      console.error('Failed to process:', record.messageId, error);
      batchItemFailures.push({ itemIdentifier: record.messageId });
    }
  }

  return { batchItemFailures }; // Only failed messages return to queue
};
```

`reportBatchItemFailures: true` enables partial batch failures — only failed messages retry, not the entire batch. Set `visibilityTimeout` higher than the Lambda timeout to prevent duplicate processing.

Monitor Lambda functions and business metrics with CloudWatch custom metrics and alarms that trigger SNS notifications.

```typescript
import * as cloudwatch from 'aws-cdk-lib/aws-cloudwatch';
import * as actions from 'aws-cdk-lib/aws-cloudwatch-actions';
import * as sns from 'aws-cdk-lib/aws-sns';
import * as subscriptions from 'aws-cdk-lib/aws-sns-subscriptions';

// SNS topic for alerts
const alertTopic = new sns.Topic(this, 'AlertTopic');
alertTopic.addSubscription(new subscriptions.EmailSubscription('oncall@example.com'));

// Lambda error rate alarm
const errorAlarm = lambdaFn.metricErrors({
  period: cdk.Duration.minutes(5),
  statistic: 'Sum',
}).createAlarm(this, 'LambdaErrorAlarm', {
  threshold: 5,
  evaluationPeriods: 2,
  alarmDescription: 'Lambda function errors exceeded 5 in 5 minutes',
  treatMissingData: cloudwatch.TreatMissingData.NOT_BREACHING,
});
errorAlarm.addAlarmAction(new actions.SnsAction(alertTopic));

// Custom business metric from Lambda
// In your Lambda code:
import { CloudWatchClient, PutMetricDataCommand } from '@aws-sdk/client-cloudwatch';

const cw = new CloudWatchClient({});

async function publishMetric(name: string, value: number) {
  await cw.send(new PutMetricDataCommand({
    Namespace: 'MyApp/Orders',
    MetricData: [{
      MetricName: name,
      Value: value,
      Unit: 'Count',
      Dimensions: [{ Name: 'Environment', Value: process.env.STAGE || 'dev' }],
    }],
  }));
}

// Usage in handler:
await publishMetric('OrdersPlaced', 1);
await publishMetric('OrderTotal', order.total);
```

`treatMissingData: NOT_BREACHING` prevents alarms from firing during low-traffic periods. Use `evaluationPeriods: 2` to avoid alerting on single-period spikes.

DynamoDB offers two capacity modes with different throttling behaviors. Choosing wrong leads to either `ProvisionedThroughputExceededException` or unexpected costs.

**Provisioned mode throttling:**
```
ProvisionedThroughputExceededException: The level of configured provisioned throughput
for the table was exceeded. Consider increasing your provisioning level with the
UpdateTable API.
```

```typescript
// Provisioned — fixed capacity, auto-scaling optional
const table = new dynamodb.Table(this, 'Table', {
  billingMode: dynamodb.BillingMode.PROVISIONED,
  readCapacity: 25,
  writeCapacity: 25,
});

// Add auto-scaling
const readScaling = table.autoScaleReadCapacity({
  minCapacity: 5,
  maxCapacity: 100,
});
readScaling.scaleOnUtilization({ targetUtilizationPercent: 70 });
```

**On-demand — pay per request:**
```typescript
const table = new dynamodb.Table(this, 'Table', {
  billingMode: dynamodb.BillingMode.PAY_PER_REQUEST,
  // No capacity settings needed
});
```

**When to use which:**
- On-demand: Unpredictable traffic, new applications, spiky workloads. ~6x more expensive per request but no throttling.
- Provisioned with auto-scaling: Predictable traffic patterns. Cheaper at scale but requires capacity planning.

**Gotcha:** On-demand tables can still throttle if traffic increases more than 2x within 30 minutes (the "adaptive capacity" ramp-up). Provisioned auto-scaling has a 1-2 minute lag — sudden spikes still throttle until scaling kicks in.

**Mitigation:** Use exponential backoff in your SDK client configuration. The AWS SDK v3 does this automatically with `maxAttempts`.

Terraform remote state in S3 with DynamoDB locking prevents concurrent modifications and enables team collaboration.

```hcl
# backend.tf — state configuration
terraform {
  required_version = ">= 1.5"

  required_providers {
    aws = {
      source  = "hashicorp/aws"
      version = "~> 5.0"
    }
  }

  backend "s3" {
    bucket         = "mycompany-terraform-state"
    key            = "production/us-east-1/terraform.tfstate"
    region         = "us-east-1"
    dynamodb_table = "terraform-locks"
    encrypt        = true
  }
}

provider "aws" {
  region = var.aws_region

  default_tags {
    tags = {
      Environment = var.environment
      ManagedBy   = "terraform"
      Project     = var.project_name
    }
  }
}
```

```hcl
# variables.tf
variable "aws_region" {
  type    = string
  default = "us-east-1"
}

variable "environment" {
  type = string
  validation {
    condition     = contains(["dev", "staging", "production"], var.environment)
    error_message = "Environment must be dev, staging, or production."
  }
}

variable "project_name" {
  type    = string
  default = "myapp"
}
```

**Bootstrap the state backend (one-time):**
```bash
aws s3 mb s3://mycompany-terraform-state --region us-east-1
aws dynamodb create-table \
  --table-name terraform-locks \
  --attribute-definitions AttributeName=LockID,AttributeType=S \
  --key-schema AttributeName=LockID,KeyType=HASH \
  --billing-mode PAY_PER_REQUEST
```

`default_tags` applies tags to all resources automatically. The DynamoDB lock table prevents two engineers from running `terraform apply` simultaneously.

SNS fan-out distributes one event to multiple SQS queues. Each subscriber processes the event independently, enabling event-driven architectures.

```typescript
import * as sns from 'aws-cdk-lib/aws-sns';
import * as sqs from 'aws-cdk-lib/aws-sqs';
import * as subscriptions from 'aws-cdk-lib/aws-sns-subscriptions';

// Topic for order events
const orderTopic = new sns.Topic(this, 'OrderEvents', {
  topicName: 'order-events',
});

// Queue 1: Send confirmation email
const emailQueue = new sqs.Queue(this, 'EmailQueue');
orderTopic.addSubscription(new subscriptions.SqsSubscription(emailQueue, {
  filterPolicy: {
    eventType: sns.SubscriptionFilter.stringFilter({
      allowlist: ['ORDER_PLACED', 'ORDER_SHIPPED'],
    }),
  },
}));

// Queue 2: Update inventory
const inventoryQueue = new sqs.Queue(this, 'InventoryQueue');
orderTopic.addSubscription(new subscriptions.SqsSubscription(inventoryQueue, {
  filterPolicy: {
    eventType: sns.SubscriptionFilter.stringFilter({
      allowlist: ['ORDER_PLACED', 'ORDER_CANCELLED'],
    }),
  },
}));

// Queue 3: Analytics
const analyticsQueue = new sqs.Queue(this, 'AnalyticsQueue');
orderTopic.addSubscription(new subscriptions.SqsSubscription(analyticsQueue));
// No filter — receives ALL events
```

**Publishing events:**
```typescript
import { SNSClient, PublishCommand } from '@aws-sdk/client-sns';

const sns = new SNSClient({});

await sns.send(new PublishCommand({
  TopicArn: process.env.ORDER_TOPIC_ARN,
  Message: JSON.stringify({ orderId: 'ord_123', total: 99.99 }),
  MessageAttributes: {
    eventType: { DataType: 'String', StringValue: 'ORDER_PLACED' },
  },
}));
```

SNS message filtering happens at the subscription level — filtered messages never reach the queue, saving costs. Each queue has its own Lambda consumer and DLQ for independent error handling.

API Gateway returns 502 when it cannot parse the Lambda response or the Lambda times out. This is the most common API Gateway error.

**Error in CloudWatch:**
```
Execution failed due to configuration error: Malformed Lambda proxy response
```

**Cause 1 — Invalid response format:**
```typescript
// WRONG: Missing required fields
export const handler = async () => {
  return { message: 'hello' }; // No statusCode or body!
};

// CORRECT: Full proxy response
export const handler = async () => {
  return {
    statusCode: 200,
    headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
    body: JSON.stringify({ message: 'hello' }), // body MUST be a string
  };
};
```

**Cause 2 — Lambda timeout:**
```
Task timed out after 3.00 seconds
```
Fix: Increase Lambda timeout in CDK:
```typescript
timeout: cdk.Duration.seconds(30),
```
And set API Gateway timeout (max 29 seconds):
```typescript
new apigateway.LambdaIntegration(fn, { timeout: cdk.Duration.seconds(29) });
```

**Cause 3 — Unhandled exception:**
```typescript
// Always wrap handler in try/catch
export const handler = async (event: APIGatewayProxyEvent) => {
  try {
    // Your logic
    return { statusCode: 200, body: JSON.stringify(result) };
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Handler error:', error);
    return {
      statusCode: 500,
      body: JSON.stringify({ error: 'Internal server error' }),
    };
  }
};
```

**body must be a string** — this is the #1 cause. `JSON.stringify()` your objects. Returning an object directly causes the malformed response error.

Terraform modules encapsulate reusable infrastructure patterns. Here's a Lambda module with all associated resources.

```hcl
# modules/lambda-api/main.tf
variable "function_name" { type = string }
variable "handler" { type = string; default = "index.handler" }
variable "runtime" { type = string; default = "nodejs20.x" }
variable "source_dir" { type = string }
variable "environment" { type = map(string); default = {} }
variable "memory_size" { type = number; default = 256 }

resource "aws_iam_role" "lambda" {
  name = "${var.function_name}-role"
  assume_role_policy = jsonencode({
    Version = "2012-10-17"
    Statement = [{
      Action = "sts:AssumeRole"
      Effect = "Allow"
      Principal = { Service = "lambda.amazonaws.com" }
    }]
  })
}

resource "aws_iam_role_policy_attachment" "basic" {
  role       = aws_iam_role.lambda.name
  policy_arn = "arn:aws:iam::aws:policy/service-role/AWSLambdaBasicExecutionRole"
}

data "archive_file" "lambda" {
  type        = "zip"
  source_dir  = var.source_dir
  output_path = "${path.module}/.build/${var.function_name}.zip"
}

resource "aws_lambda_function" "this" {
  filename         = data.archive_file.lambda.output_path
  function_name    = var.function_name
  role             = aws_iam_role.lambda.arn
  handler          = var.handler
  runtime          = var.runtime
  memory_size      = var.memory_size
  source_code_hash = data.archive_file.lambda.output_base64sha256
  architectures    = ["arm64"]

  environment {
    variables = var.environment
  }
}

output "function_arn" { value = aws_lambda_function.this.arn }
output "function_name" { value = aws_lambda_function.this.function_name }
output "role_arn" { value = aws_iam_role.lambda.arn }
```

**Usage:**
```hcl
module "api_handler" {
  source        = "./modules/lambda-api"
  function_name = "user-api"
  source_dir    = "./dist/user-api"
  environment   = { TABLE_NAME = aws_dynamodb_table.users.name }
}
```

Modules accept input variables and expose outputs. Use `source` to reference local directories or remote git repos.

Sensitive configuration should use AWS Secrets Manager or SSM Parameter Store, not plain environment variables.

```typescript
// CDK: Lambda with Secrets Manager
import * as secretsmanager from 'aws-cdk-lib/aws-secretsmanager';

const dbSecret = secretsmanager.Secret.fromSecretNameV2(
  this, 'DBSecret', 'myapp/production/database'
);

const fn = new nodejs.NodejsFunction(this, 'ApiFn', {
  entry: 'lambda/api.ts',
  environment: {
    DB_SECRET_ARN: dbSecret.secretArn,  // Pass ARN, not the value
    STAGE: 'production',
  },
});

dbSecret.grantRead(fn);  // IAM permission to read the secret
```

```typescript
// lambda/api.ts — Read secret at runtime with caching
import { SecretsManagerClient, GetSecretValueCommand } from '@aws-sdk/client-secrets-manager';

const smClient = new SecretsManagerClient({});
let cachedSecret: Record<string, string> | null = null;

async function getDbConfig() {
  if (cachedSecret) return cachedSecret;

  const response = await smClient.send(new GetSecretValueCommand({
    SecretId: process.env.DB_SECRET_ARN!,
  }));

  cachedSecret = JSON.parse(response.SecretString!);
  return cachedSecret!;
}

export const handler = async () => {
  const config = await getDbConfig();
  // config.host, config.username, config.password, config.database

  return {
    statusCode: 200,
    body: JSON.stringify({ status: 'connected' }),
  };
};
```

Cache the secret in module scope so it persists across warm invocations. Secrets Manager charges $0.40/secret/month plus $0.05 per 10,000 API calls. Use the Lambda Secrets Manager extension for automatic caching without code changes.

AWS offers two API Gateway types with different features and pricing. HTTP API is newer and cheaper; REST API has more features.

**HTTP API (v2) — recommended for most use cases:**
```typescript
import * as apigwv2 from 'aws-cdk-lib/aws-apigatewayv2';
import * as integrations from 'aws-cdk-lib/aws-apigatewayv2-integrations';

const httpApi = new apigwv2.HttpApi(this, 'HttpApi', {
  corsPreflight: {
    allowOrigins: ['https://myapp.com'],
    allowMethods: [apigwv2.CorsHttpMethod.GET, apigwv2.CorsHttpMethod.POST],
  },
});

httpApi.addRoutes({
  path: '/users/{id}',
  methods: [apigwv2.HttpMethod.GET],
  integration: new integrations.HttpLambdaIntegration('GetUser', lambdaFn),
});
```

**REST API (v1) — when you need advanced features:**
```typescript
import * as apigateway from 'aws-cdk-lib/aws-apigateway';

const restApi = new apigateway.RestApi(this, 'RestApi', {
  deployOptions: { stageName: 'prod', throttlingRateLimit: 1000 },
});
```

**Feature comparison:**
| Feature | HTTP API | REST API |
|---------|----------|----------|
| Price | $1.00/million | $3.50/million |
| Latency | ~10ms lower | Higher |
| JWT auth | Built-in | Via authorizer Lambda |
| API keys | No | Yes |
| Usage plans | No | Yes |
| Request validation | No | Yes |
| WAF integration | No | Yes |
| Caching | No | Yes |
| Request transform | Limited | Full VTL |

